column1: #FORMAT=WebAnno TSV 3.2
#Text=[0689] A novel genes URLC1 were found.

#Text=It's nucleotide sequence and the amino acid sequence encoded thereby are shown with following SEQ ID NOs in the sequence listing: TABLE-US-00013 Nucleic sequence Amino acid sequence URLC1 SEQ ID NO: 1 SEQ ID NO: 2

#Text=[0690] The results obtained above are summarized below for each of the genes of the present invention: [0691] NSC 807: KOC1; this gene encodes an hnRNA K-homology (KH) domain and an RNA recognition motif (RRM) domain.
#Text=The function of the KH domain to bind to the 5'UTR of the IGF-II (IGF2) leader 3' mRNA, may repress the translation of IGF-II during late development.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest usefulness of this gene as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0692] NSC 810: TTK; this gene encodes an S TKc domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene phosphorylates proteins on serine, threonine and tyrosine, which phosphorylation probably is associated with cell proliferation.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy.
#Text=According to the present invention, the TTK protein expressed in stable transfectant promoted the growth of COS-7 cells in a dose dependent manner.
#Text=This result suggested that over-expression of TTK exerts a transforming effect on mammalian cells.

#Text=These data reveal that TTK might be a novel oncogene for NSCLC and suggest that a promising therapeutic strategy for treating lung cancers may be established by targeting TTK. [0693] NSC 811: SDC1; this gene encodes a putative band 4.1 homologues' binding motif (4.1 m) domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene is a cell surface proteoglycan, syndecan, which is an integral membrane protein acting as a receptor for extracellular matrix.
#Text=It belongs to the group of transmembrane heparin sulfate proteoglycans.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0694] NSC 812:NMB; this gene encodes a signal peptide and a transmembrane domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene functions as a neuromedin B, a member of the bombesin family, which is an autocrine growth factors for lung carcinomas.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0695] NSC 816: PIR51; the protein encoded by the gene is localized in the nucleus and no domain was found in the protein.
#Text=The protein functions as a DNA- and RNA-binding protein; interacts with the RAD51 recombinase protein involved in DNA recombination and repair.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0696] NSC 825: ANLN; this gene encodes a PH domain, several putative functions of which have been suggested: (1) binding to the beta/gamma subunit of heterotrimeric G proteins; (2) binding to lipids, e.g., phosphatidylinositol-4,5-bisphosphate; (3) binding to phosphorylated Ser/Thr residues; and (4) attachment to membranes by an unknown mechanism.
#Text=The gene encodes an actin binding protein that interacts with cleavage furrow proteins, such as septins, and may play a role in cytokinesis.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0697] NSC 841: URLC2; this gene encodes a Jmjc domain (a domain family that is a part of the cupin metalloenzyme).
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene probably is an enzyme with unknown functions that regulates the chromatin reorganization processes.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy.
#Text=According to the present study, the suppression of URLC2 induced apoptosis of LC319 cells.
#Text=Moreover, URLC2 protein expressed in stable transfectant promoted the growth of NIH3T3 cells in a dose dependent manner.
#Text=This result suggests that over-expressed URLC2 have a transforming effect on mammalian cells.

#Text=These data reveal that URLC2 might be a novel oncogene for NSCLC and suggest that a promising therapeutic strategy for treating lung cancers can be established by focusing on the URLC2. [0698] NSC 849:GJB5; this gene encodes a gap junction protein, beta 5 (connexin 31.1).
#Text=GJB5 is a member of the connexin family (beta-type (group i) subfamily).

#Text=It is reported that one gap junction consists of a cluster of closely packed pairs of transmembrane channels, connexons, through which materials of low molecular weight diffuse from one cell to a neighboring cell.
#Text=A connexon is composed of a hexamer of connexins.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic membrane by the immunocytochemical analysis.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues and high expression in NSCLCs suggest that this gene might be useful as a diagnostic marker (i.e., in diagnosis using serum or sputum) and therapeutic target for NSCLCs. [0699] NSC 855: LNIR; this gene encodes a signal peptide, immunoglobulin, immunoglobulin C2 domain and one transmembrane domain.
#Text=The transmembrane protein encoded by the gene is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the gene may be a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0700] NSC 857: TIGD5; this gene encodes a Centromere Protein B (CENP-B).
#Text=CENP-B is a DNA-binding protein localized to the centromere.
#Text=Within the N-terminal 125 residues of the protein, there is a DNA-binding domain, which binds to a corresponding 17 bp CENP-B box sequence.
#Text=In the C-terminal 59 residues, CENP-B has a dimerization domain.
#Text=CENP-B dimers binds either a two separate DNA molecule or two CENP-B boxes on one DNA molecule, with the intervening stretch of DNA forming a loop structure.
#Text=This gene belongs to the tigger subfamily of the pogo superfamily of DNA-mediated transposons in humans.
#Text=The proteins belonging to this subfamily are related to DNA transposons found in fungi and nematodes, and more distantly to the Tc1 and mariner transposases.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene is also very similar to the major mammalian centromere protein B.
#Text=The exact function of this gene is unknown.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0701] NSC 859: URLC3; this gene does not encode any known domain, and the protein encoded by the gene has 70% similarity over 56 amino acids to an eukaryotic translation initiation factor 3 subunit (Homo sapiens).
#Text=The subunit binds to the 40s ribosome and promotes the binding of methionyl-tRNAi and mRNA (by similarity).

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0702] NSC 885: BAG5; this gene encodes a BAG domain.
#Text=Thus, the protein encoded by this gene is a member of the BAG1-related protein family.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0703] NSC 893: MPHOSP1; this gene encodes a KISc domain and microtubule-dependent molecular motors that play important roles in intracellular transport of organelles and in cell division.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene belongs to the kinesin-like protein family and interacts with guanosine triphosphate (gtp)-bound forms of rab6a and rab6b.
#Text=The protein may act as a motor required for the retrograde rab6 regulated transport of golgi membranes and associated vesicles along microtubules.
#Text=The protein has a microtubule plus end-directed motility, and is phosphorylated during the M-phase of the cell cycle.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0704] NSC 895: FAM3D; this gene encodes a protein having a signal peptide domain at the N-terminal end which is supposed to be a secretory protein, although its function remains to be elucidated.
#Text=This protein was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic granules and golgi in the immunocytochemical analysis, suggesting that this protein might be secreted.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues and high expression in NSCLCs suggest that this gene might be useful as a diagnostic marker (i.e., in the diagnosis using serum or sputum) for NSCLCs. [0705] NSC 898: URLC7; the protein encoded by this gene is localized in the nucleus and no known domain existed in the protein.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0706] NSC 903: URLC9; the protein encoded by this gene was localized in the nucleus and no known domain existed in the protein.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0707] NSC 905: URLC1; this gene encodes a TUDOR domain, for which several putative functions have been suggested: (1) RNA-binding; and (2) nucleic acid binding.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0708] NSC 909: CDCA8; the protein encoded by this gene was localized in the nucleus and no known domain existed in the protein.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0709] NSC 915: URLC10; this gene encodes 2 transmembrane domains.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene has a region with low similarity to GML.
#Text=The protein was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic granule and golgi, and as dots on the surface of the cytoplasmic membrane by immunocytochemical analysis.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0710] NSC 920: CHAF1A; no known domain has been detected to be encoded by the gene.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene has a 150 kDa subunit of chromatin assembly factor 1, which helps deposit of histones H3 acetylated H4 onto replicating DNA.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0711] NSC 947: PKP3; the gene encodes an armadillo/beta-catenin-like repeats domain (ARM).
#Text=The armadillo repeat is an approximately 40 amino acid long tandemly repeated sequence motif first identified in the Drosphia segment polarity gene armadillo.

#Text=Similar repeats were later found in the mammalian armadillo homolog beta-catenin, the junctional plaque protein plakoglobin, the adenomatous polyposis coli (APC) tumor suppressor protein and a number of other proteins.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene function as a plakophillin 3, which mediates protein-protein interactions and is a member of the armadilloprotein family.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy.
#Text=The immunohistochemical staining demonstrated that PKP3 is strongly stained in the cytoplasm of squamous cell carcinoma cells.

#Text=These data suggest that PKP3 may be a promising therapeutic and diagnostic target for treating lung cancers. [0712] NSC 948: TASK-2; this gene encodes an ion transporter domain, signal peptide (SOSUI).

#Text=This gene encodes a protein belonging to the superfamily of potassium channel proteins containing two pore-forming P domains. mRNA of this gene is mainly expressed in the cortical distal tubules and collecting ducts of the kidney.

#Text=The protein encoded by the gene is highly sensitive to external pH and this, in combination with its expression pattern, suggests that it may play an important role in renal potassium transport.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.

#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0713] NSC 956: SIAHBP1; this gene encodes an RNA recognition motif (RRM) domain, which is known as a nucleic acid binding domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene is a Ro RNS-binding protein.
#Text=It interacts with Ro RNPs to activate the function of Ro RNPs.
#Text=The protein also forms a ternary complex with a far upstream element (FUSE) and FUSE-binding protein.
#Text=It can repress a c-myc reporter via the binding with FUSE.
#Text=The transcription factor IIH is also known as the target of the protein and the protein inhibits activated transcription.
#Text=This gene is implicated in the xeroderma pigmentosum disorder.
#Text=Two alternatively spliced transcript variants exist for this gene that encode different isoforms.
#Text=Multiple polyadenyllation sites seem to exist on this gene.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy.
#Text=[0714] NSC 991: DOLPP1; this gene encodes a transmembrane domain and an acid phosphatase homologues domain.
#Text=The transmembrane protein encoded by the gene is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0715] NSC 994: DKFZP434E2318; this gene encodes a BTB/POZ domain and a Kelch domain.
#Text=The BTB/POZ domain is known to be a protein-protein interaction motif.
#Text=The BTB/POZ domain mediates homomeric dimerization and also, in some instances, heteromeric dimerization.

#Text=The POZ domain of several zinc finger proteins have been shown to mediate transcriptional repression and to interact components of histone deacetylase co-repressor complexes including N-CoR and SMART.
#Text=The Kelch domain is a beta propeller domain involved in protein-protein interactions and have some enzymatic activities like glycolate oxidase.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0716] NSC 1000: PSK-1; this gene encodes a signal peptide, a CUB domain, a Sushi domain (SCR repeat) and one transmembrane domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene is highly similar to murin Sez6, an adhesion protein which contains five sushi (SCR) domains and an extracellular CUB domain.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.

#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0717] NSC 1066: MCM8; this gene encodes an ATPase associated with a variety of cellular activities (AAA) domain and a minichromosome maintenance protein (MCM) domain.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues and high expression in NSCLCs suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0718] NSC 1075: URLC4; no known domain was detected to be encoded by the gene.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0719] NSC 1103: KCNK1; this gene encodes a protein belonging to the superfamily of potassium channel proteins containing two pore-forming P domain.
#Text=The product of this gene has not been shown to be a functional channel.
#Text=Other non-pore-forming proteins may be necessary for the activity as the functional channel.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0720] NSC 1107: URLC8; this gene encodes a double-strand RNA binding motif (DSRM) domain.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0721] NSC 1113: URLC5; no known domain was detected to be encoded by the gene.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0722] NSC 1131:SYNJ2BP; this gene encodes a PDZ transmembrane domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene may be a membrane-targeted signaling protein, containing a PDZ domain.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0723] NSC 1141: URLC11; this gene encodes 9 transmembrane domains.
#Text=The transmembrane protein encoded by the gene is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0724] NSC 1142: NAPG; no known domain was detected to be encoded by the gene.
#Text=The sequence of the predicted 312-amino acid human protein encoded by NAPG is 95% identical to bovine gamma-SNAP.
#Text=The NAPG protein mediates platelet exocytosis and controls the membrane fusion event of this process.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0725] NSC 1164: NPTX1; this gene encodes a Pentaxin/C-reactive protein.
#Text=NPTX1 is a member of the neuronal pentraxin gene family.
#Text=Neuronal pentraxin 1 is similar to the rat NP1 gene which encodes a binding protein for the snake venom toxin taipoxin.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic granules by the immunocytochemical analysis.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues and high expression in NSCLCs suggest that this gene might be useful as a diagnostic marker (i.e., for diagnosis using serum or sputum) and therapeutic target for NSCLCs.
#Text=The immunohistochemical staining demonstrated that NPTX1 is strongly stained in the cytoplasm of adenocarcinoma cells.
#Text=These data suggested that NPTX1 might be a promising therapeutic and diagnostic target for treating lung cancers. [0726] NSC 1183: BYSL; no known domain was detected to be encoded by the gene.
#Text=The protein encoded by the gene has a function of bystin, which forms a cell adhesion molecule complex with trophinin (TRO) and TASTIN that may be important for the embryo implantation.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0727] NSC 1185: URLC6; this gene encodes a zinc finger RNA recognition motif domain.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0728] NSC 1191: COX17; the protein encoded by this gene localizes in the mitochondrial intermembrane space (by similarity) and may function to transport copper to the mitochondria.
#Text=Further, the protein may be required for the expression of cytochrome oxidase.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0729] NSC 1201: SLC7A1; this gene encodes 14 transmembrane domains.

#Text=The protein encoded by this gene has strong similarity to the murine Rec-1 (Atrc 1) that functions as a cationic amino acid transporter (ecotropic retroviral receptor) which transports arginine, lysine and ornithine across the plasma membrane.
#Text=This protein was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic membrane and golgi by the immunocytochemical analysis.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0730] NSC 1240: FLJ00159; this gene encodes 4 transmembrane domains.
#Text=The transmembrane protein encoded by this gene is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0731] NSC 1246: SUPT3H; this gene encodes a transcription initiation factor .alpha.D, a 18 kD subunit.
#Text=The family including the protein encoded by the gene includes the Spt3 yeast transcription factors and the 18 kD subunit of the human transcription initiation factor .alpha.D (TF.alpha.D-18).
#Text=The determination of the crystal structure revealed an atypical histone fold.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues and high expression in NSCLCs suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0732] NSC 1254: FLJ10815; this gene encodes a transmembrane amino acid transporter protein.
#Text=This transmembrane region is found in many amino acid transporters including UNC-47 and MTR.
#Text=UNC-47 encodes a vesicular amino butyric acid (GABA) transporter, (VGAT).
#Text=The protein encode by the gene has a function a little similar to the membrane transporters of the amino acid/auxin permease (AAAP) family.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0733] NSC 1265: SLC28A2; this gene encodes an Na+ dependent nucleoside transporter.
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene functions as a sodium-coupled nucleoside transporter 2, which transports purine nucleosides and uridine.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0734] NSC 1273: FLJ32549; no known domain was detected to be encoded by the gene.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0735] NSC 1288: PTGFRN; this gene encodes a signal peptide, six immunoglobulin domains and one transmembrane domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene inhibits the binding of prostaglandin f2-alpha (pgf2-alpha) to its specific fp receptor by decreasing the receptor number rather than the affinity constant.
#Text=The protein seems to functionally couple with the prostaglandin f2-alpha receptor.
#Text=This protein was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic membrane and golgi by the immunocytochemical analysis.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.

#Text=Thus, the protein may server as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0736] NSC 1292: C17orf26; this gene encodes 3 transmembrane domains, a Zinc transporter domain and a signal peptide (SOSUI).
#Text=The transmembrane protein encoded by the gene is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.

#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0737] NSC 1295: ADAM8; this gene encodes a protein homologous to snake disintegrins, Reprolysin family propeptide and Reprolysin (M12B) family zinc metalloprotease.
#Text=Members of the ADAM family are cell surface proteins with a unique structure possessing both potential adhesion and protease domains.
#Text=The extracellular region of ADAM8 shows significant amino acid sequence homology to the hemorrhagic snake venom proteins, including the metalloprotease and disintegrin domains.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues and high expression in NSCLCs suggest that this gene might be useful as a diagnostic marker (i.e., for diagnosis using serum or sputum) and therapeutic target for NSCLCs.
#Text=The immunohistochemical staining demonstrated that ADAM8 is strongly stained in adenocarcinoma cells.
#Text=These data suggested that ADAM8 might be a promising therapeutic and diagnostic target for treating lung cancers. [0738] NSC 1306: ABCA4; this gene encodes a signal peptide and an AAA domain.
#Text=The membrane-associated protein encoded by this gene is a member of the superfamily of ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters.
#Text=The ABC proteins transport various molecules across extra- and intracellular membranes.
#Text=The ABC genes are divided into seven distinct subfamilies (ABC1, MDR/TAP, MRP, ALD, OABP, GCN20 and White).
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene is a member of the ABC1 subfamily.
#Text=Members of the ABC1 subfamily comprise the only major ABC subfamily found exclusively in multicellular eukaryotes.
#Text=This protein is a retina-specific ABC transporter which uses N-retinylidene-PE as a substrate.
#Text=The protein is exclusively expressed in retina photoreceptor cell, indicating the gene product mediates transport of an essential molecule across the photoreceptor cell membrane.
#Text=Mutations in this gene are found in patients who are diagnosed as having Stargardt disease and are associated with retinitis pigmentosa-19 and macular degeneration age-related 2.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.

#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0739] NSC 1343: GPR49; this gene encodes a signal peptide, a Leucine rich repeat N-terminal domain and a 7 transmembrane receptor (rhodopsin family).
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene belongs to the G protein-coupled receptor family, which members have a large extracellular region containing leucine-rich receptor.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0740] NSC 1362: SCAMP5; this gene encodes 4 transmembrane domains.
#Text=The transmembrane protein encoded by the gene is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0741] NSC 1389: NMU; this gene encodes an NMU domain.
#Text=Like most active peptides, the protein encoded by this gene is proteolytically processed from a larger precursor protein.
#Text=The mature peptides of the protein are 8 to 25 residues long and its C-terminus is amidated.
#Text=The protein stimulates muscle contractions, specifically, that of the gastrointestinal tract and inhibit feeding.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy.

#Text=According to the present study, the NMU protein secreted into the culture medium by stable transfectant, or the active form of the NMU peptides added into the medium promoted the growth of COS-7 cells in a dose dependent manner.
#Text=According to the immunohistochemical staining, the NMU protein was strongly stained in the cytoplasm of both adenocarcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma cells.

#Text=These data revealed that NMU might be an important autocrine growth factor for NSCLC and suggested that a promising therapeutic and diagnostic strategy for treating lung cancers may be developed by focusing on the NMU ligand-receptor system.
#Text=Furthermore, the suppression of NMU induced apoptosis in LC319 cells.
#Text=Moreover, the suppression of NMU protein by anti-NMU antibody induced growth suppression compared with controls in LC319 cells.
#Text=These results suggest that lung cancer may be treated using antibody or siRNA targeting NMU.
#Text=[0742] NSC 1395: FBN2; this gene encodes a Calcium-binding EGF-like (EGF CA) domain and an EGF like (unclassified subfamily) domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene functions as a fibrillin 2, which is an extracellular matrix protein that may regulate the formation and maintenance of extracellular microfibrils.
#Text=Mutations in FBN2 may cause congenital contractual arachnodactyly.

#Text=The lower expression of this gene in normal tissues, high expression in NSCLCs, and reduced growth, proliferation and/or survival of the transfected cells by the suppression of this gene suggest that this gene might be useful as a novel diagnostic marker and target for new drugs and immunotherapy. [0743] NSC 1420: CHDOL; this gene encodes a type I membrane protein with a carbohydrate recognition domain that is characteristic of C-type lectins in its extracellular portion.
#Text=In other proteins, this domain is involved in endocytosis of glycoproteins and exogenous sugar-bearing pathogens.
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene predominantly localizes to the perinuclear region.
#Text=This protein was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic membrane and golgi by the immunocytochemical analysis.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
#Text=Thus, the protein may serve as a good target for receptor-targeted therapy or diagnosis. [0744] NSC 1441: HSNOV1; this gene encodes an integral membrane protein DFU6 domain.
#Text=The protein encoded by this gene was mainly detected in the cytoplasmic membrane and golgi by the immunocytochemical analysis.
#Text=This transmembrane protein is supposed to be over-expressed on the surface of tumor cells but not on normal cells.
